text: Elucidation of the Tailoring Steps in Julichrome Biosynthesis by Marine Gastropod Mollusk-Associated Streptomyces sampsonii SCSIO 054 Xiaoqi Ji, Yuliang Dong, Chunyao Ling, Zhenbin Zhou, Qinglian Li,* and Jianhua Ju* ABSTRACT: The biosynthetic gene cluster governing the production of antibacterial julichromes was identiﬁed from marine gastropod mollusk-associated Streptomyces sampsonii SCSIO 054. Post- PKS assembly/tailoring enzymes JuiL, JuiM, JuiI, and JuiN represent key assembly enzymes. JuiL serves as a ketoreductase. JuiM is an acetyltransferase. JuiI carries out an intriguing biaryl coupling of two julichrome Q6 units (immediate JuiL, JuiM product) to aﬀord julichrome Q6−6. JuiN carries out tailoring steps on julichrome Q6−6, transforming Q6−6 into Q3−3. W hen marine organisms are threatened by pathogens or parasites, they appear to evolve highly eﬀective self- defense strategies.1 Many marine animals team up with symbiotic microbes to produce large amounts of chemicals with activities against various predators and/or competitors.2,3 Recent advances suggest that the antibacterial lomaiviticins A and B,4 antiviral anthranosides A−C,5 and clinical anticancer trabectedin/ET-7436 originate from symbiotic microbes of marine invertebrates likely evolved speciﬁcally for such host protective capabilities. studies, we isolated In previous Streptomyces sampsonii SCSIO 054 from a marine gastropod mollusk Batillaria zonalis collected from Daya Bay, South julichrome China Sea. This microbe produces a series of derivatives possessing a broad spectrum of biological activities against Gram-positive bacteria.7

The julichromes, or julimycins, a small family of aromatic polyketides, were ﬁrst isolated from terrestrial Streptomyces shiodaensis in the 1960s.8 To date, 28 julichrome derivatives, including 20 dimeric species, have been reported (Figure S1).7−17 Julichrome derivatives display moderate cytotoxic activity against a range of human tumor cell lines,17 as well as radical-scavenging activity.15 Julichrome representatives have also displayed signiﬁcant inhibitory eﬀects on crown gall formation and have potential as agricultural antibiotics and inhibitors of plant transformation.12 To date, however, reports of julichrome biosynthetic pathway(s) have remained scarce. To the best of our knowledge, only one such biosynthetic study has been reported. In 2014, Müller and co-workers isolated julichromes Q3−3 and Q3−5 from Streptomyces afghaniensis and identiﬁed their biosynthetic gene cluster (BGC) termed jul (Figure 1A).18 It was noted that the bacterial cytochrome P450 monooxygenase JulI catalyzes a regioselective coupling of monomeric julichrome Q6 [3 (Figure 1B)] to install a unique biaryl linkage characteristic of the dimeric julichrome Q6−6 [4 (Figure 1B)]; this was Cite This: https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/acs.orglett.0c02469 © XXXX American Chemical Society determined by in vivo gene inactivation/complementation and in vitro enzyme assays using the cell-free extract, including JulI, an FAD-containing NADH-putidaredoxin reductase (PdR), and a [2Fe-2S] putidaredoxin (Pdx).18 However, other tailoring steps involved in julichrome biosynthesis have not been reported.

We previously isolated a series of julichrome derivatives from SCSIO 054, including julichromes Q3−5 (6) and Q3−3 (7) as the main products and Q10 (1), Q11 (2), Q6 (3), Q6−6 (4), Q5 (5), Q12 (10), chrysophanol (8), and huanglongmycin A (9) as the minor products.7 We also revised the stereochemical conﬁgurations at C-9 of 6 and 7 by X-ray single-crystal diﬀraction.7 Monomeric julichromes Q10 (1) and Q11 (2) isolated from S. sampsonii SCSIO 054 provide new insight into the biosynthetic assembly of julichrome family members. Herein, we report (i) the identiﬁcation and analysis of the julichrome biosynthetic gene cluster (termed jui) from S. sampsonii SCSIO 054, (ii) the elucidation of an oxidoreductase JuiL, an acetyltransferase JuiM, and a bacterial cytochrome P450 monooxygenase JuiI involved in the biosynthesis of julichrome, clarifying a proposed biosynthetic pathway of → Q6−6, and (iii) an FAD- → Q6 julichromes of Q10 dependent oxidoreductase (epoxidase) JuiN that carries out an oxidative tailoring step with dimeric julichrome Q6−6 using in vivo gene inactivation/complementation studies. Online antiSMASH software analyses of the whole genome for S. sampsonii SCSIO 054 identiﬁed 15 putative BGCs; only one BGC was a type II PKS gene cluster termed the jui gene cluster (deposited as Genbank accession number MT799798) containing 15 open reading frames and spanning 15.1 kb (Figure 1A and Table S1). Comparison of the putative jui gene cluster and the reported jul cluster by sequence analysis revealed two clusters showing a high degree of similarity (Table S1). Eleven genes of the two gene clusters have a high degree of homology at the protein level, indicating that the jui cluster is responsible for julichrome biosynthesis in S. sampsonii SCSIO 054. In addition, there are four unannotated genes in the jui gene cluster (juiL, juiM, juiN, and juiO). To further verify our hypothesis, we inactivated juiA (ketosynthase α) in the wild-type (WT) SCSIO 054 using the λ-RED-mediated PCR-targeting mutagenesis method (Figure S2).19 Fermentation and HPLC-UV-based extract analyses for the ΔjuiA mutant strain revealed that this mutant failed to produce all of the julichrome compounds, including the main products julichromes Q3−5 (6) and Q3−3 (7) as well as the minor products julichrome Q5 (5), huanglongmycin A (9), and chrysophanol (8) (Figure 2, trace ii). type II PKS derivatives whose assembly, from acetyl-CoA, is initiated by a minimal polyketide synthase composed of β-ketoacyl synthase α (KSα) JuiA, β-ketoacyl synthase β (KSβ) JuiB, and an acyl carrier protein JuiC. The starting unit is subsequently extended by eight malonyl-CoA units to form the C-18 main chain, which is then processed by ketone reductase, aromatase, and cyclase machineries to establish the basic polycyclic scaﬀold (Figure 1B). To substantiate the julichrome polyketide skeleton biosynthesis, we inactivated four genes in the jui gene cluster, juiD (ketoacyl reductase), juiE (cyclase/aromatase), juiH (polyketide synthesis cyclase), and juiF (thioesterase) (Figures S3−S6). The resulting double crossover ΔjuiD, ΔjuiE, ΔjuiH, and ΔjuiF mutants were conﬁrmed by PCR, and subsequent HPLC-UV-based metab- olomics analyses revealed that each of these mutant strains failed to produce all of the julichrome compounds, including the main products julichromes Q3−5 (6) and Q3−3 (7) as well as the minor products julichrome Q5 (5), huanglongmycin A (9), and chrysophanol (8) (Figure S7). These data further conﬁrm the indispensibility of the jui cluster to julichrome construction and also suggest that the julichrome BGCs from diﬀerent producers are very likely conserved.

Interestingly, we had previously found that julichromes Q10 (1) and Q11 (2) from SCSIO 054 could be separated by adding XAD-16 resin to the fermentation step, providing new insight into the biosynthetic tailoring steps of julichromes. We speculated that the C-18 main chain ﬁrst formed julichrome Q10 (1) and that the C11 ketone group of julichrome Q10 (1) was then reduced to form C11 alcohol julichrome Q11 (2). Acetylation of the C11 hydroxy group of julichrome Q11 (2) would form julichrome Q6 (3); subsequently, the cytochrome P450 monooxygenase JuiI, which is highly homologous with the biosynthetic gene cluster of the reported JulI, was envisioned to couple two Q6 (3) to form dimeric julichrome Q6−6 (4). We monomers envisioned that, ultimately, julichrome Q6−6 (4) would then be converted to julichromes Q3−5 (6) and Q3−3 (7) by assorted tailoring enzymes.

On the basis of these hypotheses, the neighboring genes within the jui cluster were analyzed for genes potentially able to catalyze C11 ketoreduction. One gene, juiL, encoding an F420-dependent oxidoreductase was detected; this family of oxidoreductases plays important roles in the biosynthesis of antibiotics.20−22 For instance, TomJ can reduce 4-ethylidene- 3,4-dihydropyrrole-2-carboxylic acid to 4-ethylidene-tetrahy- dropyrrole-2-carboxylic acid in the biosynthesis of tomaymy- cin.22 Moreover, F420-dependent oxidoreductases are well- imines,22 known to catalyze redox transformations of alcohols,23 and carbon−carbon double bonds.24 To verify the juiL was disrupted by λ-RED function of recombination technology, and the resulting ΔjuiL double crossover mutant was conﬁrmed by PCR (Figure S8). Fermentation of the ΔjuiL mutant and subsequent extraction and metabolomics revealed the inability of the ΔjuiL mutant to produce the main products of WT SCSIO 054 julichromes Q3−5 (6) and Q3−3 (7). However, ablation of JuiL did, in fact, lead to the production of a species represented by a pronounced HPLC signal having the same retention time and UV proﬁle as authentic julichrome Q10 (1) (Figure 2, trace iii). The accumulation of julichrome Q10 (1) by the ΔjuiL mutant strain suggests that juiL catalyzes the reduction of the C11 ketone group of julichrome Q10 (1) to its corresponding hydroxy group.

Next, the juiM gene adjacent to juiL caught our attention as we theorized that its product, JuiM, may be responsible for acetylating the newly formed C11 alcohol of julichrome Q11 (2) (Figure 1B). The juiM gene encodes an unknown functional protein, although sequence analyses indicated its close relationship to the acetyltransferase superfamily. To probe the exact roles of juiM, a ΔjuiM mutant was constructed using the standard PCR-targeting method (Figure S9). HPLC analyses of the ΔjuiM mutant fermentation extract revealed this strain’s complete inability to produce julichromes Q3−5 (6) and Q3−3 (7), although the ΔjuiM mutant strain produced ﬁve apparent peaks (Figure 2, trace iv). LC-MS analyses and comparisons with assorted julichrome standards revealed that the ﬁve compounds generated by the ΔjuiM mutant strain corresponded to julichromes Q10 (1), Q11 (2), Q5 (5), huanglongmycin A (9), and chrysophanol (8).7 The fact that juiM inactivation resulted in the accumulation of julichrome Q11 (1) invokes JuiM as the acetyltransferase responsible for acetylating the C11 hydroxy group of Q11. Huang and co- workers isolated huanglongmycin A (9) from Streptomyces sp. CB09001 and identiﬁed its biosynthetic gene cluster termed hlm,25 the sequence of which was highly similar with that of the reported biosynthetic gene cluster of julichrome. Our data are consistent with the fact that julichrome Q5 (5), huanglongmy- cin A (9), and chrysophanol (8) are shunt products in the julichrome pathway when juiM is impaired (Figure 1B). Attempts to express JuiL and JuiM in Escherichia coli for the purpose of carrying out in vitro experiments returned only insoluble proteins insuﬃcient for enzymatic assays. Thus, in vitro enzyme assays with JuiL and JuiM could not be carried out as part of this study.

Müller et al. reported that cell-free extracts, including JulI, PdR, and Pdx, catalyzed the dimerization of julichrome Q6 (3) to aﬀord julichrome Q6−6 (4).18 Accordingly, we following mutant inactivated juiI (Figure S10) and found, strain fermentations and metabolomics, that the ΔjuiI mutant produced only julichrome Q6 (3) (Figure 2, trace v). the ΔjuiI mutant with Conversely, complementation of functional juiI led to restoration of julichromes Q3−5 (6) and Q3−3 (7) production (Figure 2, trace vi). We then overex- pressed and puriﬁed JuiI from E. coli BL21(DE3) and assayed its in vitro activities with putative substrates 1−3, 8, and 9. We also prepared ferredoxin Fdx_1499 and ferredoxin reductase FdR_0978 from cyanobacterium-type strain Synechococcus elongatus PCC 79421726 as the redox partner proteins for JuiI; in total, this set of redox enzymes would ensure the requisite two-electron transfer from NADPH to the heme-iron reaction center (Figure S11).27 Incubation of 3, and only 3, with JuiI in the presence of Fdx_1499, FdR_0978, and NADPH at 30 °C and 400 rpm for 2 h yielded a new product with the same HPLC retention time and UV proﬁle as authentic 4 (Figure S13). Compounds 1, 2, 8, and 9 all failed to serve as JuiI substrates (Figure S12). Consequently, we concluded that julichrome Q11 (2) must be acetylated prior to JuiI-catalyzed dimerization; in other words, julichrome Q6 (3) is JuiI during julichrome biosynthesis.

Structurally, the wild-type predominant adduct julichrome Q3−3 (7) is derived from julichrome Q6−6 (4) via a series of oxidation reactions. However, obvious tailoring enzyme candidates for this chemistry had never been reported. Intrigued by the prospect that such tailoring enzymes might be encoded within the jui cluster, we carefully analyzed the jui gene cluster and found that juiN, which encodes an FAD- dependent oxidoreductase, might participate in julichrome Q6−6 structural reﬁnement or tailoring. Sequence analysis of JuiN revealed that JuiN contains both GxGxxG28 and GD29 sequences; both are associated with FAD binding associations displayed by class A ﬂavin monooxygenases (FMOs).30 To interrogate the role(s) of juiN in julichrome assembly, we inactivated the juiN gene and obtained the ΔjuiN mutant the JuiN deﬁcient strain (Figure S13). Fermentation of followed by HPLC analysis of the ΔjuiN mutant fermentation extract revealed that a major julichrome intermediate having the same molecular weight and HPLC retention time as authentic julichrome Q6−6 (4) accumulated in this mutant. In trans complementation of the ΔjuiN mutant restored the production of julichromes Q3−3 (7) and Q3−5 (6) to levels on par with that of WT SCSIO 054 (Figure 2, traces vii and viii). These data demonstrated that juiN does, in fact, carry out tailoring steps on julichrome Q6−6 (4), speciﬁcally trans- forming Q6−6 into Q3−3 (7) and Q3−5 (6).

Finally, antimicrobial screens revealed that julichrome Q6−6 (4) displays antimicrobial activities against Gram-positive including Micrococcus luteus and Bacillus subtilis, pathogens, with MIC values ranging from 2 to 64 μg/mL; in contrast, julichromes Q3−3 (7) and Q3−5 (6) showed relatively minor activity.7 In this work, the cytotoxicity of julichromes was determined using the brine shrimp lethality assay (BSLA).31 The BSLA results showed that the lethality concentration (LC50) of julichrome Q6−6 (4) was 43.2 μg/mL; in contrast, julichromes Q3−3 (7) and Q3−5 (6) showed no lethal activity against brine shrimp. JuiN likely serves as a self-defense strategy to protect the julichrome producer from the antimicrobial activities of julichrome Q6−6 (4). However, that is not to say that the JuiN is the sole means of self-defense employed by this organism. The yield of julichrome Q6−6 (4) generated in the ΔjuiN mutant that is comparable to that of compounds 6 and 7 produced by the WT julichrome producer (Figure 2, traces i and vii) suggests that WT SCSIO 054 likely employs multiple mechanisms of julichrome resistance, juiN being just one of these. In addition, we also envision a symbiotic feature of this chemistry. Speciﬁcally, when mollusk host Batillaria zonalis are threatened, SCSIO 054 produces toxic julichrome Q6−6 (4) to defend the symbiont pairing against various antagonists. In the absence of such external threats, and to avoid toxic julichrome Q6−6 (4) from harming the producing microbe, juiN eﬀectively constitutes one of the drug resistance genes that modiﬁes Q6−6 (4) to the substantially less bioactive species Q3−3 (7) and Q3−5 (6), thereby limiting intracellular julichrome toxicities.

In summary, we have identiﬁed and characterized the jui gene cluster in S. sampsonii SCSIO 054 by genome scanning, bioinformatics analyses, gene inactivations/complementations, and in vitro biochemical experiments. In so doing, we have clariﬁed the biosynthetic pathway of julichrome (Q10 → → Q6−6). JuiL reduces the C11 keto group of julichrome Q6 Q10, enabling JuiM to acetylate the C11 OH moiety (of Q11) immediately prior to dimerization of julichrome Q6 to render the dimer; notably, JuiI catalyzes Q6 dimerization and, in so doing, linkage. The oxidase JuiN appears to catalyze post-PKS assembly/tailoring steps by converting Q6−6 to the epoxidized and less bioactive species Q3−3 and Q3−5. As such, JuiN protects S. sampsonii from its own secondary metabolism by restricting the accumulation of antimicrobial and cytotoxic Q6−6. Ultimately, these ﬁndings set the stage for a comprehensive understanding of julichrome biosynthesis and are projected to be vital in future eﬀorts to assemble julichrome-based antimicrobial drug leads. *sı Supporting Information The Supporting Information is available free of charge at https://pubs.acs.org/doi/10.1021/acs.orglett.0c02469.
